This directory contains gene expression data measured in several disease-relevant tissues gathered from ~1,400 asthma subjects from the Asthma BioRepository for Integrative Genomic Exploration (ABRIDGE) along with extensive clinical phenotype data on each subject.  This data has been successfully processed through a quality control pipeline (QC+). 

A git repository containing the current and previous versions of all pipeline code can be found in the main directory.  This repository does *not* contain any input or output data files.

The contents of the project directories are summarized below:

* @Code/@
    Code for pipeline used to generate QC+ ABRIDGE gene expression data.  Primary driver scripts for running the pipeline have file names that start with numbers.  These scripts can be submitted to the capecod cluster queue using the "qBR" command.  Absolute paths are specified in each script, but should be inspected prior to usage.  The "knitr" sub-directory contains code for knitr documents that describe the data as it progresses along the QC pipeline. 

* @Input/@
    Pre-existing files (ABRIDGE questionnaire and ID mapping table) or ones created by "Code/1_create_input_data.R" necessary for running the QC pipeline.  There are a few versions of the ABRIDGE questionnaire dataset present here, but the most current version is called "abridge_en_sp.e2_dist.csv".

* @Logs/@
    Log files and other documentation output by the QC pipeline.  Data for particular runs are found in directories named following a "YYYYMMDD" date format.

* @Output/@
    PDF reports generated to describe the data as it progressed along the QC pipeline along with the final R data objects (.rda) containing the gene expression, phenotype, and principal components of gene expression data.  Data for particular runs are found in directories named following a "YYYYMMDD" date format. 

The two most important sub-directories are "20130206_ForDistribution" and "20130206_InternalMaster".  The former contains a subset of the data found in the latter, namely only data for subjects that gave consent for data sharing across investigators participating in ABRIDGE.  The latter folder contains the full ABRIDGE dataset that can be used for internal Channing-based analyses.  These two datasets can be considered stable and appropriate for use in downstream analyses.  Any future changes to the data should be made to a copy of the internal master dataset.

The remaining three folders with earlier dates reflect major timepoints in the development of the pipeline.  These datasets should not be used in downstream analyses and are kept for historical purposes.

Pooja, for the $5-genome-pipeline project that you will be collaborating on, some of the data preparation can be done ahead of time.  These are the requirements specified by the developers:

* Human whole-genome paired-end sequencing data in unmapped BAM (uBAM) format
* One or more read groups, one per uBAM file, all belonging to a single sample (SM)
* Input uBAM files must additionally comply with the following requirements:
** filenames all have the same suffix (we use ".unmapped.bam")
** files must pass validation by ValidateSamFile
** reads are provided in query-sorted order
** all reads must have an RG tag
* Reference genome must be Hg38 with ALT contigs

I think you can focus on the first item in this list for the time being.    Robert has found the following lead on converting files to ubam format: https://software.broadinstitute.org/gatk/documentation/article?id=6484

The current raw data files are:

@/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/AGES/data/dna/exome/reykjavik_exome_seq/data/raw/sysg1.cs.yale.edu\:3010/@

README for estimated mtDNA copy number:

Both mitochondrial DNA copy number and mitochondrial DNA sequence data are provided by the
University of Michigan IRC to each study for deposit in the TOPMed dbGap area.  Copy number
estimates are provided for studies in data freeze 8.

Mitochondrial DNA copy number for each TOPMed sample is estimated by applying the fastMitoCalc 
software (Jun Ding et al (2015)) to harmonized build 38 mappings of TOPMed deep whole genome 
sequencing data.  The estimated mitochondrial copy number is twice the ratio of average mitochondrial 
sequencing depth to average autosomal sequencing depth.

In addition to the estimated copy number and the two component sequencing depths, the table 
identifies each DNA sample by its NWD identifier, study PI, study name, phs number, sequencing
center and QC date.  It provides four sequencing quality control metrics derived from autosomal DNA.
"pct.contam" is the estimated level of DNA sample contamination from verifyBamID in (fractions of a)
percent.  "isize" is the median sequencing insert size.  "pct.dp10" and "pct.dp20" give the fraction
of the genome covered (in percent) to at least depth 10 and at least depth 20.

The 13 columns in the table are:

   NWD: TOPMed sample ID
   PI: Study PI
   study: Study name
   PHS: dbGaP phs accession number
   seq.ctr: Sequencing center
   qc.date: Date of QC in Michigan (shortly after receipt of the sequence data in Michigan)
   mito.cn: Estimated mtDNA copy number
   mito.dp: Average mitochondrial sequencing depth
   auto.dp: Average autosomal sequencing depth
   pct.contam: Estimated level of DNA sample contamination estimated by verifyBamID (in percent)
   isize: Median sequencing insert size (base pairs)
   pct.dp10: Fraction of the genome covered to at least depth 10 (in percent)
   pct.dp20: Fraction of the genome covered to at least depth 20 (in percent)

Reference:
J. Ding et al (2015).  Assessing mitochondrial DNA variation and copy number in lymphocytes 
of ~2,000 Sardinians using tailored sequencing analysis tools.  PLoS Genetics, v.11, e1005306.

Estimated telomere length from whole-genome sequencing (WGS) samples
The TelSeq method was used to perform telomere length estimation on the TOPMed WGS data. Final telomere length (TL) estimation was performed on a set of 93,219 samples from Freeze 6a whose sequencing reads were available for analysis at the TOPMed IRC at the time of analysis. 

Details of the TelSeq method are found in Ding et al.(1). TelSeq calculates an estimate of individual TL using counts of sequencing reads containing a fixed number of repeats of the telomeric nucleotide motif TTAGGG. Given that 97.9% of the TOPMed data was sequenced using read lengths of 151 or 152, we chose to use a repeat number of 12. These read counts are then normalized according to the number of reads in the individual with between 48% and 52% GC content, to adjust for potential technical artifacts related to GC content. 

For questions, contact Rasika Mathias (rmathias@jhmi.edu) or Margaret Taub (mtaub@jhsph.edu).

1. Ding, Z. et al. Estimating telomere length from whole genome sequence data. Nucleic Acids Res 42, e75, doi:10.1093/nar/gku181 (2014).

There has been a reference dataset produced by Meg Parker and maintained by Robert Chase here:

/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/data/projectdata/rerpc/king_data/

This dataset has been used a reference or comparing new genotype data; but it is (may be) missing a few subjects.  We thought to produce a similar dataset with the same markers, updated to include all of the samples in the Unified VCF.  This dataset should be plink-formatted.

This dataset contains as much data as possible on all COPDGene subjects at 59 SNP loci that are used as references on the Illumina Methylation 850K/EPIC chip.  It is intended to be used a reference in the Methylation pipeline to detect sample issues to to mis-plating, etc.

Here is the IGH data from the 143 samples we have processed so far.
Each folder is named after the sample and should contain 5 files:

R1.fastq
R2.fastq 

contain the raw reads we generated. In some folders they will be named SampleName_LibraryNumber_R*_001.fastq. That is due to how the data was produced. I couldn't fix this but they are the only files containing R1 or R2 in the file name so it should be manageable on your end hopefully.

consensus_complete.txt

contains the consensus reads we generated by merging the two raw reads in R1 and R2 and by combining read pairs with the same UMIs. Although ending on txt, this is in fastq format

allfiltered_numbered.fasta

contains the consensus reads after identical consensus reads are collapsed. They are named RunningNumber_NumberOfCollapsedReads.

igblast.out.IGH.parsed.txt

contains parsed output from igblast for the reads in allfiltered_numbered.fasta. The format is tab separated and columns are:
read name,Sequence type,Vsegment,Dsegment,Jsegment,CDR3 sequence,Ambigous Vsegments,Placeholder,Isotype,read sequence, position of mismatches (comma separated)

sftp collab@kalee.ucsc.edu

user: collab
password:

and then 

cd data/BWH/share/

The COPDGene whole blood microRNA data need to be organized. All sequencing was performed at PPM. There are several considerations when thinking about how to best organize these data: A) The data arrived in several batches; however, there are two main umbrellas for datasets: 1) The initial microRNA sequencing that was performed in 2 pilot studies and 7 batches: 
/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/analyses/rerpc/mirnaseqBCBIO/2018-10-09\_fo\r_rpc15\_raw/batch\_copdgene\_mergedfiles\_June282019/sampleconfig/final/2019-08-13\_sampleconfig
2) The blocker-based sequencing data that was generated following application of 3 blockers of highly expressed microRNAs, where the * represents a sample: 
/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/analyses/rerpc/bcbio_mirnaseq/ppm_december2019/*/sampleconfig/final/*/counts_mirna.tsv
B) The initial data for [A2] had a bad batch (plate 5) that needed to be resequenced. The repeat sequencing of "plate 5" was complicated because it occurred after a change in sequencers and a change in small RNA seq protocol for PPM. So the repeats batch (https://chanmine.bwh.harvard.edu/issues/21821#change-139521) was sequenced with a single 96 well plate sequenced across 4 flowcells (batches) with each sample spread over multiple flowcell lanes. Previously one 96 well plate was sequenced on one flowcell. As noted in issue 21821, which I re-opened, there is no current path to counts data resulting from these raw sequencing data. C) The initial data from [A2] with the bad batch (plate 5) removed have been used in some published analyses and there is a pre-QC "freeze" located at: 
/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/analyses/rebdh/craigMiRna/mirSeqCounts_noFilt_blockFreeze2_20200522.rds
These data were given to our collaborators at Colorado and the relevant publication is https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34777474/ There is a README containing the python code for the recommended cleaning of these data, created by Michele Gentili: 
/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/analyses/rebdh/craigMiRna/READMEforCleaning
D) A later data analysis freeze was generated by me for a project with Michael McGeachie: 
/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/analyses/rebdh/craigMiRna/mirSeqPheno_filt_blockFreeze2_20200608.rds
/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/analyses/rebdh/craigMiRna/mirSeqCounts_filt_blockFreeze2_20200608.rds
And the code to complete the analysis starting with these data is in changit: 
https://changit.bwh.harvard.edu/rebdh/craigMiRna/blob/master/copdGeneMirDE_blockFreeze2.Rmd
https://changit.bwh.harvard.edu/rebdh/craigMiRna/blob/master/copdGeneMirDE_blockFreeze2.html
It is unclear how to best organize these datasets in the CHAMMPS structure; however, they are currently spread far and wide and it would be great to reach a consensus on how to best consolidate and simplify this data set. Thank you, Brian

Ongoing discussions about producing a more workable version of the TOPMed freeze.8 WGS data has led to this dataset as one candidate.

This is a folder that contains genotype files generated from TOPMED FREEZE8 separated by chromosome.

/proj/regeps/regep00/studies/COPDGene/data/rnaseq/BLOOD/QCed_data/eqtl_files/genotype_files/TOPMED8_FREEZE3

Here are brief steps that I took to generate these files:

1. Filter BCF files by "PASS" filter and convert them to VCF from TOPMED FREEZE8 WGS data folder.
2. Annotate the VCF files
3. Use plink2 to filter by MAF 0.01 and use Rscript to convert NWD IDs to our COPDGene ID
4. Use Rscript to filter the VCF so that it only has SNP information for individual samples.

I have written a README for each folder, so it should be relatively easy to backtrace the steps that I took.

The CRA Project is expecting delivery of batches of methylation data from the TopMed DCCs.  One component of our EPIC pipeline is to compare genotypes for 59 QC SNPs on the chip to previous genotyping for each sample to determine concordance.   This dataset can be used as a reference panel to compare against, and should contain the most complete set of genotypes at these 59 loci for as many CRA samples as we can locate.

This dataset was prepared in order to provide reference genotyping that the TopMed DCC could use to check for concordance in its WGS datasets.

August 13, 2018

Dear Dr. Weiss, Dr. Cho, and Dr. Su,

As part of TOPMed quality control (QC) procedures, the TOPMed Data Coordinating Center (DCC)
performs checks of genotype concordance between prior array data and TOPMed whole genome
sequencing (WGS) data to identify possible sample identity issues. We are requesting prior array
data from your studies CRA and CRA_CAMP to enable this check.

In September 2016 and April 2017 you provided us with PLINK files for prior array data, respectively,
from MEGAchip (CRAEXT_MEGAchip_UW_2015) and from another GWAS source (2015_NHLBI_DCC_GWAS_QC_AGCT).
However the fam files for these were based on NWD IDs. We need fam files based on subject identifiers for the
subject from whom the sample was taken. One of the main reasons for this is that concordance checks are
used to identify potential sample swaps. In addition, your Phase 3 contribution appears to contain many
more samples. We would greatly appreciate it if you could provide us with PLINK files of prior GWAS array
data using subject identifiers for subjects in CRA and CRA_CAMP.

These data can be transferred to us via the TOPMed dbGaP Exchange Area (EA).  If the EA is used, the
file(s) should be password-protected, as other TOPMed investigators besides the DCC have access to the EA.
These files will be promptly downloaded by the DCC and then immediately deleted from the EA. Alternatively,
the files can be transferred directly from the study to the DCC via a secure file exchange system.

Once the prior array data is acquired, the DCC will run an in-house pipeline to perform the concordance check
with existing TOPMed WGS data. The results will be used to generate a QC report that will be returned to the
study investigators, detailing any potential sample identity issues raised by the concordance check.

Instructions for uploading to the EA can be found on the TOPMed website nhlbiwgs.org: Data/Data Sharing/Data
sharing through dbGaP Exchange Areas (https://www.nhlbiwgs.org/data-sharing-through-dbgap-exchange-areas),
section “Details regarding uploading and downloading data”.  When you have uploaded the files, please reply to
me with the name of the file(s), the date uploaded, and the genome build for the data. You can send a text to
me (205-292-5242) with the password; please also include your name or the study name in the text.

We thank you for your cooperation in these matters. If there is another person in your study more appropriate to
address this request, please forward this email to them.  We would appreciate it if you could provide us with this
data by August 27, 2018 if possible. Please do not hesitate to follow up with additional questions or concerns.

Sincerely,

Cecelia Laurie

TOPMed Data Coordinating Center

This dataset represent all of the raw and QC data that was part of the Innate Immunity PGA of the early 2000s.  I will do my best to describe the basic layout, but please contact [[cdnm-grants-portal:John Ziniti]] if you would like more details.  There are two primary sub-folders here (InnateImmunity and SeattleSNPs).  In each sub-folder, there is a single folder for each gene that was targeted for seqeuncing (133 genes for InnateImmunity, 103 for SeattleSNPs).  Sequencing and SNP-calling were performed at a remote location.  Tools to interpret the sequencing data and SNP calls were a mix of locally-developed python code, and some third-party tools (PHASE, Arlequin, etc.).  Data were downloaded from the remote site, and fed through an automated pipeline.  As with many projects, the pipeline processing changed throughout the lifetime of the project, so there may be some minor differences between files available for some genes.

There are a few conventions in the naming of files, etc. that will be helpful:

* There were 4 populations of subjects in this project.  Each subject id is prefixed with a code that indicates which population it is from:
** @A@ = African-American 
** @D@ = ??
** @E@ = European
** @H@ = Hispanic
These letters also appear in filenames to indicate that the file only contains the subset of subjects belonging to that population.  The letter @ in a filename refers to everyone.
* The letters @pc@ preceded by a number indicates a "percent cutoff", usually referring to a minor allele frequency
* @Masked@ indicates that the gene sequence was fed through the repeat masker before being used in any given tool

Using TLR2 as an example, the primary data for each gene are:

@TLR2/TLR2.fsa@: This is the sequence of the gene, as determined by the remote site
@TLR2/TLR2.prettybase.txt@: These are the called genotypes for each of the sequenced subjects.  The fields are POSITION, SUBJECT, ALLELE1, ALLELE2.  The position is relative to the sequence in @<GENE>.fsa@

These inputs were then re-formatted and fed to a variety of tools:

* Metadata
** @TLR2.relpb.txt@: Prettybase data where positions are relative to the start of gene instead of the start of the reference sequence
** @TLR2.abstorel.txt@: A mapping file of "absolute" positions to "relative" positions
** @TLR2_context*bp.fsa@: context sequence around the SNP of interest
** @TLR2.primers.csv@: Primers used in sequencing

* Summary statistics
** TLR2_10.0pcgenoggt.jpg
** TLR2_10.0pcgenogid.jpg
** @TLR2_ac.*@: Allele counts in various formats
** @TLR2_af.*@: Allele frequencies
** @TLR2_gc.*@: Genotype counts
** @TLR2_gf.*@: Genotype frequencies
** @TLR2.hw.*@: Hardy-Weinberg calculations

* PHASE (http://stephenslab.uchicago.edu/phase/download.html) and PHASE2: generated phased haplotypes
** @TLR2*.loci@
** @TLR2*.phase@
** @TLR2*.phase2@
** @TLR2_10pcA.fasta@
** @TLR2*.pout@
** @TLR2*.pout2@

* Various Pairwise LD calculations:
** @TLR2_*incmissmpop*.jpeg@
** @TLR2_dprimeldplot*.jpg@
** @TLR2_hapldplot*.jpg@

* Arlequin (http://cmpg.unibe.ch/software/arlequin35/):
** @TLR2_10pcincmissmpop.arp@

* Haplotyper (http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~junliu/Haplo/docMain.htm)
** @TLR2*.htin@: Input
** @TLR2*.htout@: Output
** @TLR2_hap*@
** @TLR2.hap*@

* SNPper
** @TLR2.gif@: Is really a PNG?  A "map" of the gene.
** @TLR2.snpper.html@

* GOLD (http://csg.sph.umich.edu/abecasis/Gold/index.html)
** @TLR2*gold*@

Run a qc/analysis of blank fields in the PPMI Lung Transplant REDcap.

The current PPMI Transplant REDcap contains lab instrument to capture lab values. The data requested from RPDR needs to be modified to only display lab values with dates that are closest to the date of enrollment.  Those lab values then need to be modified for subjects that have no lab values up to date. 

1. The first script that was written gives the number of subjects in REDCap with no lab values that have lab data present in RPDR.
This set of patients is then saved to a dataframe called   'rem_patient_labs'.

2. This data frame is then consolidated to extract lab tests done closest to the date of the enrollment of the subject to the study. 


3. The goal is to produce a final data frame with the closest lab date to enrollment for each subject.

1. Using passcode, download data to desired path/folder. (Move to reben)
2. Using Access sql queries, link Contact Information, Demographics, MRN by appropriate identifiers.

4. Select fields from the final unified data sheet that you want to import into REDCAP
5.Rename fields in the final unified data sheet (with the desired variables) to the appropriate fields in the Samsung Asthma Registry REDCAP
6. Import Data via API or data import tool

## This describes the columns of the summary statistics generated in Yengo et al. (2018)
## Meta-analysis of genome-wide association studies for height and body mass index in ~700,000 individuals of European ancestry

----------------------
Columns description
----------------------

SNP:                        RS ID
CHR:                        Chromosome
POS:                        Physical position (Genome build hg19)
Tested_Allele:              Allele corresponding to the effect size (BETA/BETA_COJO)
Other_Allele:               Other allele
Freq_Tested_Allele_in_HRS:  Frequency of the tested allele in the Health and Retirement Study (from 8,552 unrelated participants).
BETA:                       Marginal SNP effect size.
SE:                         Standard error of the effect size.
P:                          P-value measuring the significance of the marginal effect.
N:                          Sample size.
BETA_COJO:                  Conditional effect size from the software GCTA version 1.9 using HRS as linkage disequilibrium panel.
SE_COJO:                    Standard error of the conditional effect size.
P_COJO:                     P-value measuring the significance of the conditional effect.

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27863252 Many common variants have been associated with hematological traits, but identification of causal genes and pathways has proven challenging. We performed a genome-wide association analysis in the UK Biobank and INTERVAL studies, testing 29.5 million genetic variants for association with 36 red cell, white cell, and platelet properties in 173,480 European-ancestry participants. This effort yielded hundreds of low frequency (<5%) and rare (<1%) variants with a strong impact on blood cell phenotypes. Our data highlight general properties of the allelic architecture of complex traits, including the proportion of the heritable component of each blood trait explained by the polygenic signal across different genome regulatory domains. Finally, through Mendelian randomization, we provide evidence of shared genetic pathways linking blood cell indices with complex pathologies, including autoimmune diseases, schizophrenia, and coronary heart disease and evidence suggesting previously reported population associations between blood cell indices and cardiovascular disease may be non-causal.

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28209224 *BACKGROUND*: Genome-wide association studies have so far identified 56 loci associated with risk of coronary artery disease (CAD). Many CAD loci show pleiotropy; that is, they are also associated with other diseases or traits. *OBJECTIVES*: This study sought to systematically test if genetic variants identified for non-CAD diseases/traits also associate with CAD and to undertake a comprehensive analysis of the extent of pleiotropy of all CAD loci. *METHODS*: In discovery analyses involving 42,335 CAD cases and 78,240 control subjects we tested the association of 29,383 common (minor allele frequency >5%) single nucleotide polymorphisms available on the exome array, which included a substantial proportion of known or suspected single nucleotide polymorphisms associated with common diseases or traits as of 2011. Suggestive association signals were replicated in an additional 30,533 cases and 42,530 control subjects. To evaluate pleiotropy, we tested CAD loci for association with cardiovascular risk factors (lipid traits, blood pressure phenotypes, body mass index, diabetes, and smoking behavior), as well as with other diseases/traits through interrogation of currently available genome-wide association study catalogs. *RESULTS*: We identified 6 new loci associated with CAD at genome-wide significance: on 2q37 (KCNJ13-GIGYF2), 6p21 (C2), 11p15 (MRVI1-CTR9), 12q13 (LRP1), 12q24 (SCARB1), and 16q13 (CETP). Risk allele frequencies ranged from 0.15 to 0.86, and odds ratio per copy of the risk allele ranged from 1.04 to 1.09. Of 62 new and known CAD loci, 24 (38.7%) showed statistical association with a traditional cardiovascular risk factor, with some showing multiple associations, and 29 (47%) showed associations at p < 1 × 10-4 with a range of other diseases/traits. *CONCLUSIONS*: We identified 6 loci associated with CAD at genome-wide significance. Several CAD loci show substantial pleiotropy, which may help us understand the mechanisms by which these loci affect CAD risk.

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28604731 Persistent insomnia is among the most frequent complaints in general practice. To identify genetic factors for insomnia complaints, we performed a genome-wide association study (GWAS) and a genome-wide gene-based association study (GWGAS) in 113,006 individuals. We identify three loci and seven genes associated with insomnia complaints, with the associations for one locus and five genes supported by joint analysis with an independent sample (n = 7,565). Our top association (MEIS1, P < 5 × 10-8) has previously been implicated in restless legs syndrome (RLS). Additional analyses favor the hypothesis that MEIS1 exhibits pleiotropy for insomnia and RLS and show that the observed association with insomnia complaints cannot be explained only by the presence of an RLS subgroup within the cases. Sex-specific analyses suggest that there are different genetic architectures between the sexes in addition to shared genetic factors. We show substantial positive genetic correlation of insomnia complaints with internalizing personality traits and metabolic traits and negative correlation with subjective well-being and educational attainment. These findings provide new insight into the genetic architecture of insomnia.

h3. SUMMARY

The miRBase database provides a searchable online repository for published microRNA sequences and associated annotation.  miRBase also provides a gene naming and nomenclature function in the miRBase Registry.

Release 22 of the database contains 38589 entries representing hairpin precursor miRNAs, expressing 48885 mature miRNA products, in 271 species.  The data are freely available to all through the web interface at http://www.mirbase.org/ and in flatfile form from ftp://mirbase.org/pub/mirbase/.

h3. CHANGES SINCE RELEASE 21

10031 new hairpin sequences and 13149 new mature products have been added, an increase in the number of sequences of over a third.  The first miRNAs in 48 new species are reported.  115 hairpins and 496 mature sequences have  changed names; the overwhelming majority of these changes are additions of lettered or numbered suffixes to differentiate related loci.  87 misannotated and duplicate sequences have been deleted.  See the miRNA.diff file for the full description of changes.

The "high confidence" microRNA dataset (as described in Kozomara and Griffiths-Jones, NAR 2014) is available on the FTP site.

h3. FILES

The following files are available from the above ftp site:

  miRNA.dat     - all entries in (almost) EMBL format
  hairpin.fa    - predicted miR stem-loop sequences in fasta format
  mature.fa     - mature sequences in fasta format
  miRNA.dead    - entries removed from the database
  miRNA.diff    - differences between the current and last release

The genomes/ directory contains gff files of genome coordinates for 152 species.  See the individual files for the genome assemblies used.

The database_files/ directory contains dumps of the MySQL relational database that is used to generate the web pages.  The documentation for this subset of files is non-existent - use at your peril!

h3. LICENSE

miRBase is in the public domain. It is not copyrighted.  You may freely modify, redistribute, or use it for any purpose.  See
ftp://mirbase.org/pub/mirbase/CURRENT/LICENSE for details. 

h3. HOW TO CITE THE miRNA DATABASE

The miRBase database is described in the following articles:

miRBase: annotating high confidence microRNAs using deep sequencing data.
Kozomara A, Griffiths-Jones S.
Nucleic Acids Res. 2014 42:D68-D73

miRBase: integrating microRNA annotation and deep-sequencing data.
Kozomara A, Griffiths-Jones S.
Nucleic Acids Res. 2011 39:D152-D157

miRBase: tools for microRNA genomics.
Griffiths-Jones S, Saini HK, van Dongen S, Enright AJ.
Nucleic Acids Res. 2008 36:D154-D158

miRBase: microRNA sequences, targets and gene nomenclature.
Griffiths-Jones S, Grocock RJ, van Dongen S, Bateman A, Enright AJ.
Nucleic Acids Res. 2006 34:D140-D144

The miRNA Registry.

h3. FEEDBACK

Any queries about data, web services, naming requests or other feedback should be directed to mirbase@manchester.ac.uk.

The IMPROVE study is a multicentre, observational study, which recruited 3,711 men and women aged between 55 to 79 years with at least three cardiovascular risk factors but without symptoms of CVD.

Recent advances in highly multiplexed immunoassays have allowed systematic large-scale measurement of hundreds of plasma proteins in large cohort studies. In combination with genotyping, such studies offer the prospect to 1) identify mechanisms involved with regulation of protein expression in plasma, and 2) determine whether the plasma proteins are likely to be causally implicated in disease. We report here the results of genome-wide association (GWA) studies of 83 proteins considered relevant to cardiovascular disease (CVD), measured in 3,394 individuals with multiple CVD risk factors. We identified 79 genome-wide significant (p<5e-8) association signals, 55 of which replicated at P<0.0007 in separate validation studies (n = 2,639 individuals). Using automated text mining, manual curation, and network-based methods incorporating information on expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL), we propose plausible causal mechanisms for 25 trans-acting loci, including a potential post-translational regulation of stem cell factor by matrix metalloproteinase 9 and receptor-ligand pairs such as RANK-RANK ligand. Using public GWA study data, we further evaluate all 79 loci for their causal effect on coronary artery disease, and highlight several potentially causal associations. Overall, a majority of the plasma proteins studied showed evidence of regulation at the genetic level. Our results enable future studies of the causal architecture of human disease, which in turn should aid discovery of new drug targets.

*SomaLogic plasma protein GWAS summary statistics*

In 2018, a team at CEU led by Ben Sun and Adam Butterworth published a paper in Nature describing a genomewide association study in 3301 participants from the INTERVAL study in whom a SomaLogic aptamer-based plasma protein assay had been run, measuring ~3600 proteins (see Sun et al., Nature, 2018). In total, we identified 1,927 associations (“pQTLs”) with 1,478 proteins, greatly enhancing our understanding of the genetic determinants of human plasma protein levels.

In addition to making the individual-level genetic and proteomic data available on request via the European Genome-Phenome Archive (https://ega-archive.org/studies/EGAS00001002555), we are also making publically available the full genetic association summary statistics.

 

Files can be downloaded from Box.com: https://app.box.com/s/u3flbp13zjydegrxjb2uepagp1vb6bj2

Users can either download files from the website directly, or alternatively connect to the site using rclone or lftp. For instructions on how to use rclone or LFTP, please contact Adam Butterworth (asb38@medschl.cam.ac.uk).


There are 3,283 folders on the site, one for each of the 3,283 SOMAmers used to assay the 2,995 proteins that passed quality control in the analyses. Each folder, which is named according to the ID of the SOMAmer, contains 22 gzipped text files, one for each autosomal chromosome analysed. (The same set of variants was analysed for each of the 3,283 SOMAmers).

Within each results file, the columns are in the order:

VARIANT_ID chromosome position Allele1 Allele2 Effect StdErr log(P)

where the columns include:

VARIANT_ID = VARIANT_ID in the format <chromosome>_<position>_<index>
chromosome and position in build37.
Effect size with respect to Allele1 (the effect allele).
StdErr = Standard Error of effect size
log(P) = log10(p-value)

 

The Box.com site also contains a .csv file that lists the SOMAmer ID, target protein, full name of the target protein, and Uniprot ID for the 3,283 SOMAmers.

The Library of Integrated Cellular Signatures (LINCS) is an NIH program which funds the generation of perturbational profiles across multiple cell and perturbation types, as well as read-outs, at a massive scale. The LINCS Center for Transcriptomics at the Broad Institute uses the L1000 high-throughput gene-expression assay to build a Connectivity Map which seeks to enable the discovery of functional connections between drugs, genes and diseases through analysis of patterns induced by common gene-expression changes. These files represent L1000 data generated during the LINCS Pilot Phase (2012-2015), as well as profiles generated for more specific purposes, such as assay development and validation projects or testing custom compounds or non-standard cell lines (not part of the core LINCS cell lines). Note: Related GEO projects include (a) Additional L1000 and RNA-Seq data used to validate the assay and improve the inference model, available at GSE92743 (b) The LINCS “production phase” (also termed Phase II, 2015-2020) which is generating an additional cohort of L1000 data, available at GSE70138.

*Overview*

The ability to manipulate the mouse genome, together with the wealth of disease models, inbred strains and genomic resources, makes the mouse the premier model organism for genetic approaches to mammalian biology. Over a century of mouse genetics has provided scores of inbred strains, spontaneous and engineered mutations, making the mouse unsurpassed as a model system for investigating human disease. Access to complete sequence of multiple inbred strains will add to these resources and will become a permanent foundation for a systems biology approach to phenotypic variation in the mouse.

The Mouse Genomes Project uses next generation sequencing technologies to sequence the genomes of key laboratory mouse strains. The project consists of two arms:

* Short-read sequencing of many laboratory mouse strains and identification of sequence variation (SNPs, short insertions and deletions, and larger structural variations) relative to the C57BL/6J mouse reference genome.
* De novo genome assembly and strain specific gene annotation of the most highly used strains.

*Sequence variation*

We and our collaborators have used short-read sequencing to identify SNPs, indels, and structural variations relative to the C57BL/6J mouse reference genome. The strains that have been sequenced and are in our variation catalog are:

RELEASE NOTES:

===============

*  Build 152 include the following changes and improvements from Build 151:

        - RS clustering using SPDI canonical allele notation.

         - NCBI Variant Overprecision Correction that left shift variants in repeated regions and merged RS.  This reduced redundant records and fewer RSIDS in the dataset.

*  dbSNP Entrez search (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/snp/) is still based on human Build 151 and will be updated to Build 152 later with new changes to eUtils.   When the migration is completed all current eUtils report formats (RS docsum XML, ASN.1, FASTA, and FLAT text) will be retired.   Only the new eSummary XML report will be supported.  Sample eSummary XML and specs are on available for review on GitHub (https://github.com/ncbi/dbsnp/tree/master/specs).

*  The earlier beta release based on Build 151 is archived here (https://ftp.ncbi.nih.gov/snp/redesign/archive/b151/)

 

The next build 153 with major content updates will be in Q2 2019.

dbSNP Team

Build 156 of dbSNP (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/snp/) with over 1.1 billion                                                                                                                  RefSNP (rs) records across the human genome is now available. Build 156 includes                                                                                                              data from 1000Genomes, TOPMed, gnomAD, and many other submitters, as well as                                                                                                                  NCBI ALFA release 2 with over 900 million rs and allele frequencies from dbGaP                                                                                                                studies. All data is open-access and unrestricted for web searching, FTP                                                                                                                      download, and API access.

The goal of dbSNP is to provide a comprehensive reference set of human single                                                                                                                 nucleotide variants and small-scale insertions and deletions, as well as                                                                                                                      population frequency, molecular consequence, ClinVar clinical interpretation,                                                                                                                 publication, and genomic and RefSeq mapping information for both common and                                                                                                                   clinical mutations. More information on dbSNP somatic mutations can be found                                                                                                                  at (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/snp/docs/analysis/somatic/).                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               dbSNP would like to thank all of the submitters and community members who shared                                                                                                              their data with the larger community.

Using combined GWAS genotypes on each genotyping platform and the 1000 Genomes Project Phase 3 Integrated Release Version 5 and Haplotype Reference Consortium (HRC version 1.1 2016) as reference panels, we imputed the genotypes of markers for 8020 samples in Affymetrix dataset, 7164 samples in Illumina HumanHap dataset, 8970 samples in Illumina OmniExpress dataset, 7963 samples in HumanCore Exome dataset and 10652 samples in OncoArray dataset. SNP genotypes were imputed in two steps. First, genotypes on each chromosome were phased using ShapeIT (v2.r837). In second step, phased data were submitted to Michigan Imputation Server. The server use Minimac3 Minimac to impute the phased genotypes to approximately 47 million markers in the 1000 Genomes Project mixed population and 39 million in HRC EUR population. TOPMed Freeze 9 Variant Callset
=================================

Overview
-------------
Data freeze 9 is based on variant discovery using 143,415 participants in 37 TOPMed studies, 60,540 samples sequenced by NHGRI Centers for Common Disease Genomics (CCDG) and 2,504 1000 Genomes Project samples deeply sequenced by the New York Genome Center.  For this data freeze we have relaxed the sequencing quality control criteria to include samples with up to 10% estimated DNA sample contamination (previously 3%) and at least 15 x average coverage (previously 30 x).  There are no thresholds on the fractions of the genome covered to at least 10 x or 20 x.  In addition to 139,088 samples sequenced in the TOPMed program (after excluding samples with no consent), this freeze includes 19,382 samples from TOPMed studies that were sequenced by CCDG for a total of 158,470 TOPMed study samples, plus 2,504 1000 Genomes Project samples and a grand total of 160,974 samples.  The genotypes for samples from CCDG-only studies will be returned separately to CCDG.

After variant filtering, this produces a dataset with approximately 781 M SNP records and 62 M short indel records which pass variant QC, and an additional 104 M records where support vector machine (SVM) filtering suggests that genotypes are less reliable.  These variant counts are slightly smaller than the corresponding numbers in data freeze 8 due to omitting sites which show no variation in TOPMed samples.  Multiallelic variants are represented as biallelic records on consecutive rows.  Hence, especially for short indels, the number of distinct sites will be smaller than the total number of records.

Three versions of the genotypes and variants are provided in separate directories:

* minDP0   = genotype calls for all individuals at all sites.
* minDP10 = genotypes for all individuals at all sites, with genotypes shown as missing ("./.") when an individual has less than 10x sequencing depth at this site.
* sites        =   sites-only files, no genotypes.

Each directory contains 23 single-chromosome .bcf files and the corresponding .csi index files.  These can be converted to .vcf format using 'bcftools view' for use with other VCF-compatible software tools such as `vcftools`, `EPACTS`, and `plink-1.9'.  These 3 directories in the dbGaP exchange area for data freeze 9 total ~5 terabytes.  Statistically phased haplotypes using Eagle 2.4 (Dec 13, 2017) will be provided when they are ready.

List of Included Samples
------------------------------
Analysts for each individual study will have access to genotypes for that study's participants.  Cross study genotypes are posted in the dbGaP exchange area.  The totals below double-count samples which belong to more than one study.  The available subsets and sizes are as follows:

Variant Calling and Filtering
-------------------------------------
The latest version of the GotCloud/vt pipeline is used for calling both SNPs and indels, focusing on bi-allelic SNPs and indels.  Briefly, candidate SNP and indel sites are called from the aligned reads for each sample.  These are combined and normalized across all samples, accounting for tandem repeats.  Genotypes for each individual are called on the union of all variant sites and merged across samples.  Variant filtering uses a support vector machine (SVM) classifier.  HapMap3 and Omni2.5 polymorphic SNPs serve as positive training labels and variants showing 3 or more Mendelian inconsistencies among 38,866 samples that are duplicates or members of nuclear families serve as negative labels.  In addition to improved SVM filtering using local LD information, all variants in the NCBI GWAS catalog are flagged in the INFO field and marked as PASS.  Variant functional annotation is provided from snpEff 4.3t (build 2017-11-24 10:18), using the GRCh38.86 database.

FILTER reasons
---------------------
The BCF files are VCF 4.2 compatible, thus have self-explanatory descriptions of the FILTER, INFO, and FORMAT fields.  All files summarize site filtering information in the FILTER column.

For SNPs and Indels, possible FILTER values include:
* PASS   - The variant site passes all filters
* SVM     - The variant shows an SVM score more negative than -0.5 (hence fails the SVM filter)
* CEN     - The variant falls in a centromeric region with inferred reference sequence
* DUP2   - The variant shows more than 2 percent discordance between duplicates
* TRI2     - The variant shows more than 2 percent Mendelian inconsistencies
* MIS2    - The variant shows more than 2 percent of samples below depth 10
* DISC    - The variant shows more than 5 percent duplicate or Mendelian inconsistencies
* EXHET - The variant has excess heterozygosity and HWE p-value less than 1e-6
* CHRXHET - The variant has excess heterozygosity in male chrX (meaning that the male diploid model likelihood is much higher than male haploid model).  This filter is applied only in the non-pseudo-autosomal region of chromosome X.

INFO fields
---------------
The INFO column in VCF contains the following information.  The VCF header contains self-explanatory descriptions of these fields as well.  Primary INFO fields include:

* AVGDP - Average depth per sample without read-level filtering
* AC        - Alternate allele counts
* AN        - Total number of alleles
* GWAS  - Variant in the GWAS catalog; INFO field shows the previous FILTER value
* SVM     - Score from the Milk-SVM classifier for variant filtering (failure threshold is -0.5)
* ANN     - (Annotated sites only) Variant functional annotations from snpEff (details below)

Additional INFO fields (used for SVM filtering) include:

* FIBC_P  - Pooled excess homozygosity estimate (inbreeding coefficient):  "+" means excess homozygosity, "-" means excess heterozygosity compared to HWE
* HWE_SLP_P - Signed log 10 p-value for testing Hardy-Weinberg equilbrium ignoring population substructure (matches sign of FIBC_P)
* FIBC_I  - Excess homozygosity (inbreeding coefficient) adjusted for population structure and calculated from genotype likelihoods:  "+" means excess homozygosity, "-" means excess heterozygosity compared to HWE
* HWE_SLP_I - Signed log 10 p-value for testing Hardy-Weinberg equilbrium after adjusting for population substructure (matches sign of FIBC_I)
* MAX_IF  - Maximum individual-specific alternate allele frequency
* MIN_IF   - Minimum individual-specific alternate allele frequency
* LLK0      - Null likelihood (for debugging purposes)
* BETA_IF - Coefficients for intercept and each eigenvector used to calculate individual specific allele frequency
* ABE     - Mean of allele balance criterion across all heterozygous genotype calls (higher than 0.5 indicates bias towards the reference allele)
* ABZ     - Mean of Z-scores for allele balance across all heterozygous genotype calls (positive indicates bias towards the reference allele)
* BQZ     - Z-score for testing association between base qualities and alleles
* MQZ     - Z-score for testing association between mapping quality and alleles
* CYZ     - Z-score for testing association between position in the sequence read and alleles
* STZ     - Z-score for testing association between strand and alleles
* NMZ     - Z-score for testing association between number of mismatches per read and alleles
* IOR      - Estimated inflation of base quality in log 10 scale
* NM0     - Average number of mismatches in reads showing the reference allele
* NM1     - Average number of mismatches in reads showing the non-reference allele
* FMIS10  - Fraction of samples with depth below 10 x
* MAX_HM3_R2 - Largest r2 to any HapMap3 variant within 1Mb
* LOG_HM3_BUDDY_03 - Number of HapMap3 variants within 1Mb with r2 >= 0.3, in log10(1+x) scale
* LOG_HM3_BUDDY_05 - Number of HapMap3 variants within 1Mb with r2 >= 0.5, in log10(1+x) scale
* LOG_HM3_BUDDY_08 - Number of HapMap3 variants within 1Mb with r2 >= 0.8, in log10(1+x) scale
* LOG_HM3_DIST_03     - Distance to nearest HapMap3 variant within 1Mb with r2 >= 0.3, log10(1+x) scale
* LOG_HM3_DIST_05     - Distance to nearest HapMap3 variant within 1Mb with r2 >= 0.5, log10(1+x) scale
* LOG_HM3_DIST_08     - Distance to nearest HapMap3 variant within 1Mb with r2 >= 0.8, log10(1+x) scale
* DUP_NH_ALL - Number of duplicate samples with genotype depth >= 10 and one or more non-reference alleles.  This is used as the denominator to calculate duplicate discordance.
* DUP_NH_DIS - Number of duplicate samples with genotype depth >= 10 and a discordant genotype.  This is used as the numerator to calculate duplicate discordance.
* TRI_NH_ALL - Number of trios (1) whose genotype depths are all 10 or greater, (2) genotypes are informative for evaluating Mendelian consistency, and (3) the genotypes are not all homozygous reference. This is used as the denominator to calculate Mendelian discordance.
* TRI_NH_DIS - Number of trios (1) whose genotype depths are all 10 or greater, and (2) genotypes indicate Mendelian inconsistency. This is used as the numerator to calculate Mendelian discordance.

Formatting details for annotations:
Variants are annotated with snpEff 4.3t, using the GRCh38.86 database.

* ANN     - Variant functional annotations from snpEff:  'Allele | Annotation | Annotation_Impact | Gene_Name | Gene_ID | Feature_Type | Feature_ID | Transcript_BioType | Rank | HGVS.c | HGVS.p | cDNA.pos / cDNA.length | CDS.pos / CDS.length | AA.pos / AA.length | Distance | ERRORS / WARNINGS / INFO'

*Manuscript*: [[cdnm-grants-portal:Intestinal microbe-associated sphingolipids are associated with childhood food allergy]]

Having touched base with our collaborator, I think it might be the best use
of time for us to make sure we can do the analyses requested on the
existing closed ref data. So, if it's okay with you, the objectives of our
meeting tomorrow could be to make sure we do (or I know how to do) the following:


1) Create a biom file with only the 265 infant samples with anonymized IDs for external use

2) Access a mapping file with both vid and corresponding anonymized IDs
for external use so I can merge in limited metadata and add qiime output, with a plan
to delete the vid before sending to collaborators

 - Ideally the above files would be in their own directory

3) Make sure I know how to execute the following qiime commands through my
ssh client, and add the results to the mapping file:

 a) Summarize taxa at taxonomic ranks 2-7

 b) Calculate alpha diversity measures

 c) Use PICRUSt to impute the predicted metagenome and collapse to taxonomic ranks 2 and 3

This dataset uses the samples samples as the 2016_VDAART_Microbiome Dataset, but is called against the 97% similarity version of Greengenes instead of th 99%, allowing it to be used with downstream tools such as PICRUSt that depend on the 97% Greengenes. 
cdnm_microbiome_pipeline \
    -r /proj/rerefs/reref00/BerkeleyLab/greengenes/gg_13_5_otus/rep_set/97_otus.fasta \
    -t /proj/rerefs/reref00/BerkeleyLab/greengenes/gg_13_5_otus/taxonomy/97_otu_taxonomy.txt \
    `find 1[67]*/ -name '*.fastq.gz'`

SUBJECT: ECHO Extant Microbiome Data Transfer and Harmonization 
TARGET AUDIENCE: Cohort/Site PIs, Cohort/Site Data Managers 
POINT OF CONTACT: Data Analysis Center via the ECHO Help Desk 
Dear ECHO Cohort/Site PIs and Data Managers,  

We are excited to begin the transfer of extant microbiome data. If you have extant microbiome data (e.g., 16S rRNA), please submit your demultiplexed sequences and the corresponding panel, analysis, batch, participant, and specimen files according to the attached Standard Operating Procedure (SOP-EAW-016: Formatting Instructions for the Transfer of Extant Microbiome Data).

Also attached to this email is Appendix A, which is an example Excel file to demonstrate how to fill out the files, and Appendix B, which is the Excel template file that should be completed with your cohort’s data.

These materials are also available as a zip file in the ECHOPortal Resource Library.

Please complete this data transfer by Friday, October 7, 2022.

If you have questions about how to prepare or transfer these files, please send them to the ECHO Help Desk. 

 

Sincerely, 

Lisa Jacobson and Diane Catellier, ECHO Data Analysis Center (DAC)
